V-204392 - File Permissions/Ownership Match Vendor Values
============================================================

Command: rpm -Va | grep permission/ownership/group changes
----------------------------------------
FAIL: The following files have permissions, ownership, or group
membership that differ from vendor RPM defaults:

.M.......  c /boot/grub/grub.cfg
.M.......  g /etc/lvm/cache/.cache
.M.......  g /var/lock/iscsi
.M.......  g /var/lock/iscsi/lock
.M.......  g /boot/initrd-4.19.0+1.img
.M.......    /etc/dhcp/dhclient.d/chrony.sh
.M.......  c /etc/machine-id
.M.......  g /etc/udev/hwdb.bin
.M.......  g /var/lib/systemd/random-seed

Remediation: rpm --setugids and rpm --setperms for affected packages.
</FINDING_DETAILS>
				<COMMENTS>Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:

Answer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml
Key Name: XCP-ng
Index: 2

[ValidTrueComment]:
The automated check identified system files whose permissions, ownership, or group membership differ from vendor-provided RPM package values on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. The scan executed 'rpm -Va' and found deviations in the M (permissions), U (user), or G (group) attributes compared to the RPM database. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-010010, all system file attributes must match vendor values to prevent unauthorized modification of system binaries and configuration files. Remediation: (1) Identify the package for each affected file: rpm -qf [filename]. (2) Reset user and group ownership: rpm --setugids [packagename]. (3) Reset permissions: rpm --setperms [packagename]. (4) If changes were intentional and documented, obtain ISSO/ISSM approval and document the deviation in the POA&amp;M. The system administrator must investigate each mismatch to determine if unauthorized modification occurred.
        

</COMMENTS>
				<SEVERITY_OVERRIDE />
				<SEVERITY_JUSTIFICATION />
			</VULN>
			<VULN>
