Index: 2

[ValidTrueComment]:
The automated check found that the XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system allows accounts with blank or null passwords to authenticate. The scan detected the 'nullok' option in /etc/pam.d/system-auth and/or /etc/pam.d/password-auth, which permits authentication without a password for accounts that have no password set. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-010290, the operating system must not allow accounts configured with blank or null passwords. This represents a CAT I (high severity) finding because it could allow unauthorized access to the system. Remediation: (1) Remove all instances of 'nullok' from /etc/pam.d/system-auth. (2) Remove all instances of 'nullok' from /etc/pam.d/password-auth. (3) Verify no accounts exist with empty passwords: awk -F: '($2 == "") {print}' /etc/shadow. (4) Set passwords for any accounts found without one. The system administrator must ensure all accounts have valid passwords.
        

</COMMENTS>
				<SEVERITY_OVERRIDE />
				<SEVERITY_JUSTIFICATION />
			</VULN>
