V-204425 - SSH Must Not Allow Empty Passwords
============================================================

Command: grep -i PermitEmptyPasswords /etc/ssh/sshd_config
Result: #PermitEmptyPasswords no

PASS: SSH daemon does not allow authentication with empty passwords.
</FINDING_DETAILS>
				<COMMENTS>Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:

Answer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml
Key Name: XCP-ng
Index: 1

[ValidTrueComment]:
The automated check verified that the SSH daemon on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system does not allow authentication using empty passwords. The scan checked /etc/ssh/sshd_config for the PermitEmptyPasswords directive. The setting was confirmed as 'no' (or defaulting to 'no' when not explicitly set), which prevents SSH clients from authenticating with accounts that have no password configured. This meets the RHEL 7 STIG requirement (RHEL-07-010300) that the SSH daemon must not allow authentication using an empty password. SSH is the primary remote access method for XCP-ng Dom0 administration, making this control critical for preventing unauthorized remote access. Finding: Not a Finding.
        

</COMMENTS>
				<SEVERITY_OVERRIDE />
				<SEVERITY_JUSTIFICATION />
