V-204438 - BIOS GRUB2 Boot Authentication
============================================================

Firmware: BIOS
Command: grep -iw grub2_password /boot/grub2/user.cfg
Result: 

FAIL: GRUB2 superuser password not found or not using PBKDF2-SHA512.
Remediation: Run 'grub2-setpassword' to set an encrypted boot password.
</FINDING_DETAILS>
				<COMMENTS>Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:

Answer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml
Key Name: XCP-ng
Index: 2

[ValidTrueComment]:
The automated check found that this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system with BIOS firmware does not have a GRUB2 superuser password configured or the password is not using PBKDF2-SHA512 encryption. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-010482, BIOS systems must require authentication to boot into single-user and maintenance modes. Without boot authentication, an attacker with physical or console access could boot into single-user mode and gain root access without credentials. Remediation: (1) Run 'grub2-setpassword' to set an encrypted GRUB2 superuser password. (2) Verify the password is set: grep -iw grub2_password /boot/grub2/user.cfg. The system administrator must configure boot authentication immediately.
        

</COMMENTS>
				<SEVERITY_OVERRIDE />
				<SEVERITY_JUSTIFICATION />
