V-204457 - Default Permissions UMASK 077
============================================================

Command: grep -i ^UMASK /etc/login.defs
Result: UMASK           077

PASS: UMASK is set to 077.
</FINDING_DETAILS>
				<COMMENTS>Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:

Answer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml
Key Name: XCP-ng
Index: 1

[ValidTrueComment]:
The automated STIG check verified the UMASK setting in /etc/login.defs on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. The check ran "grep -i ^UMASK /etc/login.defs" and confirmed that UMASK is set to 077. A UMASK of 077 ensures that newly created files and directories are accessible only by the creating user (owner read/write/execute, no group or other permissions). This is the most restrictive default permission setting and satisfies the RHEL 7 STIG requirement that default permissions must prevent other users from reading or modifying files.

</COMMENTS>
				<SEVERITY_OVERRIDE />
				<SEVERITY_JUSTIFICATION />
