V-214799 - Cryptographic Hash of System Files Matches Vendor Values
============================================================

Command: rpm -Va --noconfig | grep "^..5"
----------------------------------------
FAIL: The following system files have cryptographic hash values
that differ from vendor RPM defaults:

S.5....T.    /usr/sbin/dhclient-script

Investigate each mismatch. Reinstall affected packages:
  rpm -qf [filename]  (identify package)
  yum reinstall [package]  (restore vendor files)
</FINDING_DETAILS>
				<COMMENTS>Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:

Answer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml
Key Name: XCP-ng
Index: 2

[ValidTrueComment]:
The automated check found system files whose cryptographic hashes differ from vendor RPM package values on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. The scan executed 'rpm -Va --noconfig' and detected MD5 hash mismatches for non-configuration files. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-010020, system file hashes must match vendor values to ensure integrity. Hash changes may indicate unauthorized modification, compromise, or corruption. Remediation: (1) Identify the package for each file: rpm -qf [filename]. (2) Reinstall affected packages: yum reinstall [package]. (3) Investigate whether changes were authorized. (4) Review system audit logs for evidence of tampering. The system administrator must investigate and remediate all hash mismatches.
        

</COMMENTS>
