V-255927 - Restrict Access to Kernel Message Buffer
============================================================

Command: sysctl kernel.dmesg_restrict
Result: kernel.dmesg_restrict = 0

FAIL: kernel.dmesg_restrict is not set to 1.
Remediation: Add 'kernel.dmesg_restrict = 1' to /etc/sysctl.conf
then apply: sysctl -p
</FINDING_DETAILS>
				<COMMENTS>Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:

Answer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml
Key Name: XCP-ng
Index: 2

[ValidTrueComment]:
The automated check found that the kernel message buffer is not restricted on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. The kernel.dmesg_restrict sysctl parameter is not set to 1. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-010375, unprivileged access to dmesg must be restricted. Remediation: (1) Add 'kernel.dmesg_restrict = 1' to /etc/sysctl.conf. (2) Apply: sysctl -p. The system administrator must restrict kernel message buffer access.
        

</COMMENTS>
